      <hedline>
        <hl1>On Preserving Rail Service</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Laura A Radcliffe on March 9 article on Gov John G Rowland's proposal to grind to a halt Danbury and Waterbury lines of Metro-North Commuter Railroad in Connecticut as well as Shoreline East service (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Regarding your article (''3 Rail Lines or a Penny a Gallon?'' March 9). For Gov. John G. Rowland to consider a cutback on commuter rail service is shortsighted.</p>
        <p>The roadbeds are a valuable asset for use now and in the future. Once closed down they could never be replaced, as dependence on cars would only increase until the time when fossil fuels are depleted.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Regarding your article (''3 Rail Lines or a Penny a Gallon?'' March 9). For Gov. John G. Rowland to consider a cutback on commuter rail service is shortsighted.</p>
        <p>The roadbeds are a valuable asset for use now and in the future. Once closed down they could never be replaced, as dependence on cars would only increase until the time when fossil fuels are depleted.</p>
        <p>As our population continues to grow, no one would intentionally close down commuter rail lines. The railroads are the only sane way to provide transportation. Beefing up railroad lines throughout the United States to reduce the overload on highways is the only sane way.</p>
        <p>Let's be visionary. Let's not save the drivers a penny a gallon. Let's bite the bullet. Think of the future! As a senior citizen and for all those who follow me, I want good public transportation.</p>
        <p>LAURA A. RADCLIFFE  Weston</p>
      </block>
